Renewed Scripture, Renewed Hope: Disability Through the Lens of the Raised Type New Testament

Introduction

The Bible has influenced language, imagery, and society, becoming what Hull describes as the 'norm' for countless generations in Western society. Its narratives also hold the potential to empower individuals; this is particularly relevant for disabled people for whom biblical stories have the potential to offer a source of liberation given the roles and contributions of disabled figures. Despite the few references to characters with disabilities in the New Testament, figures like Paul—who may have lived with a visual impairment following his conversion—embody the impact that disabled individuals had on both society and history. Yet, accessing these narratives presents barriers. Historically, the majority of people in Western nations were illiterate and biblical knowledge was passed through church paintings, stained glass, and oral tradition; perhaps this is more accessible than modern Christianity following the scripture. As we navigate the modern world, challenges persist in terms of accessibility and barriers affecting disabled people’s ability to access the Bible's pages independently.

Context

AI art and printing share a closer relationship than we might initially think. Printmaking and the printing press was a pivotal milestone in the history of art and technology, revolutionising how we produce and consume information. Similarly, AI has initiated another evolutionary leap that impacted these processes and prompted us to further our understanding of creativity. The intent behind this project is to focus on the intersection of accessibility, generative AI, and religion. The main question here is how religious objects can best be approached to encourage a dialogue among a wider audience, using generative AI. Paine criticises the idea that encountering religious objects is limited to a disembodied experience and suggests that religious objects have more to offer than appreciation for their aesthetic: "It’s not until one has seen religious objects in use – either in an actual way or in some virtual way – that they truly come alive, that one can get a glimpse, if you like, into the souls of these objects".

Building upon this, this project explores generative AI to further explore the Raised Type New Testament, originally in Greek and formally translated and printed by the New York American Bible Society. This project requires access to the University of Glasgow's Special Collections for digitisation. This is available for public access. Prior booking is necessary at the University of Glasgow Archives & Special Collections. Many thanks go to Robert McClean for introducing archival handling principles, guiding this project and showcasing the objects virtually and in person.

The essence of religious artefacts, including the Raised Type New Testament, can be connected with their historical context. This connection is not only about the physicality of these objects but also their role in the practice of faith, as highlighted by Paine's perspective. Paine argues that religion transcends a system of ideas, emphasising it as a practice rooted in tangible objects. In this light, the Raised Type New Testament embodies more than just a text; it represents the history of a practice of engaging with the sacred, making it a critical tool for inclusivity and accessibility in religion.

Objectives

The overall objective of this project is to engage with the Raised Type New Testament beyond its religious context by presenting it as a cultural artifact. It aims to explore to situate the object within its cultural and historical context. By doing so, it aims appeals to a broader audience that is interested not only in theology but also hidden histories of disablity and accessible practices. The Raised Type New Testament ought to be recognised not just as a religious scripture but as a cultural object that reflects early accounts of accessible practices. The intended outcomes are:

  • Develop a multimedia object to acommpany the Raised Type New Testament based on biblical stories focusing on a re-imagined script with the disabled people.
  • Use AI technologies to transform the Raised Type New Testament into various accessible formats, including audio narration, and visual imagery, ensuring that the text is approachable for users with diverse accessibility needs.
  • Communicate the religious and cultural content of the Raised Type New Testament, ensuring that the resulting narratives remain true to the original text.

Knowledge & Themes

  • Contemporary Religion: The project examines into the new testaments's relevance in a post-Christian and post-secular context, presenting the Raised Type New Testament as both a religious text and a critical artifact of accessibility history.
  • Cultural Preservation: Acknowledging the physical delicacy of the Raised Type New Testament, this project explores how generative AI can help engage a broader audience with this unique format, sparking dialogue about an often-overlooked theme—disability.
  • Historical and Cultural Significance: The exhibition of the Raised Type New Testament aims to underscore its influence on European culture—and by extension, global history as a result of colonialism—inviting a diverse audience to engage with its lesser-known stories and historical impact.

Human-AI Collaboration

This project embraces AI as a collaborator, acknowledging that while AI does not possess creative intention in the human sense, its outputs can reshape the human artist's intent in a meaningful way. AI can potentially shift creative expression—challenging us to reconsider the relationship between the medium and the creative ideas. This includes how we value art and whether it is the labour behind or other aspects, think of oil paintings! With using existing generative AI models, there is no intensive manual effort that is traditionally associated with artmaking. This might be present in projects that program their AI model and digitise their training data, from the start to the finish, but perhaps is not in the usual use of models like Dall-e. This prompts us to question how we value art when the labour behind it becomes less visible and more intellectual. You might also want to consider how immersion in the creative process changes, as AI allows for rapid experimentation of concepts that might otherwise would require hours of labour to envision. In this, we find a new form of value: the capacity to explore more ideas and engage in deeper reflection.

In this project, the initiation of ideas was human, and the production of art and output was AI. I decided on the prompts and ideas, then had the AI generate them. I digitised the Raised Type New Testament and had that converted into machine-readable text. Then, based on the page I randomly selected to show how this process can be conducted I decided to let AI narrate it, convert the narration into audio, generate images based on the narration, decide on the description of the music to match the narration, and based on that, I combined the different multimedia elements and used subtitles. Following these, I made ai write a description of the object and the video that it generated to see how it could be placed in GLAMs. I then proofread it. You might think of this collaboration as the generative ai models i used were a talented mutlimedia artist in all domains, and I am the project manager giving feedback on what works and what doesn’t for our clients.

You might think, all of these can be done manually—so what is the point? Well, in this project, I considered that with little funding for both humanities and disability studies, this project had low funding environments in GLAMs. With reduced funding, GLAMs (galleries, libraries, archives, and museums) are reluctant to give up any income, no matter how minimal.

How Does Generative AI Work?

Generative AI refers to a class of artificial intelligence technologies that generate new content, ranging from text and images to music and code, based on the patterns and data it has learned from. This type of AI can be incredibly powerful and adaptable. Below, I’ll explain how generative AI typically works, focusing on two popular methods: Generative Adversarial Networks (GANs) and Transformer models.

Generative Adversarial Networks (GANs)

  • Architecture: A GAN consists of two neural networks — the generator and the discriminator. These two networks are trained simultaneously in a competitive setting where the generator tries to create fake data, and the discriminator attempts to differentiate between real and generated data.
  • Training Process:
    • The generator takes in random noise as input and generates samples (like images).
    • The discriminator receives both real data (from the actual dataset) and fake data (from the generator). Its job is to accurately classify the data as real or fake.
    • During training, the generator continuously learns to produce more convincing data while the discriminator becomes better at detecting fake data.
    • This process continues until the generator produces data indistinguishable from real data, ideally fooling the discriminator.
  • Outcome: The result is a generator that can create realistic-looking images, text, or other data types that mimic the style and variety of the input dataset.

Transformer Models

  • Architecture: Transformers are designed based on self-attention mechanisms that weigh the significance of different words in a sentence, irrespective of their position. This model architecture allows the AI to evaluate the context of a word within its entire surrounding text, making it exceptionally good for generating human-like text.
  • Training Process:
    • The model is trained on a large corpus of text data where it learns the probability distribution of words appearing in certain contexts.
    • It processes each word or token by looking at all other tokens in the sentence at the same time, calculating which tokens contribute more to the next word’s prediction.
    • Over time, the model fine-tunes its predictions to generate coherent and contextually relevant text based on the input it receives.
  • Outcome: Once trained, Transformer models can generate text that flows logically and maintains consistency over longer stretches, making them ideal for applications like chatbots, content creation, and more.

Methodology

Research Question

  • "How can Human-AI collaboration effectively transform the raised type New Testament into an inclusive cultural object, facilitating deeper engagement and dialogue among a wider audience?"

Workflow

Technologies Used

  • Digitisation & Optical Character Recognition

    • The process began with digitising the text through high-resolution scanning using an iPhone 14 camera, which provided the necessary image quality. Following this, the file size was reduced using Microsoft Paint to facilitate easier handling. To convert the captured image into machine-readable text, the imagetotext platform was used, which offers its services free of charge and without requiring login information. At the core of this conversion process lies Optical Character Recognition (OCR) technology. OCR uses pattern recognition and machine learning algorithms, such as neural networks, to meticulously identify and classify each character captured within the document. This intricate process includes comparing the elements of the scanned image against a database of known characters and interpreting the text's structure. The goal is to transform the text in the image into a digital format to allow text searching and editing.

  • Narration & Commentary

    • For narration purposes, "BibleGPT" was used, which is a custom library available at ChatGPT. This variant is developed through a process called fine-tuning, which involves training the original model with additional datasets, integrating bespoke instructions, and a range of capabilities tailored to specific use. The development of BibleGPT involved enhancing the base model's capabilities by introducing targeted data sets, thereby expanding its comprehension and response capabilities in context-specific domains, aka the bible. Access to the standard ChatGPT platform is available at no cost and requires users to register for an account. BibleGPT requires access to the GPT-4, which needs subscription behind a paywall. BibleGPT was developed by Daniel Abraham.

  • Image Generation

    • The script-to-image generator is an advanced tool designed to convert textual scripts into visual images, effectively “automating the content creation process”. Developed as a specialised library within the ChatGPT by OpenAI, it uses the Dall-e model to interpret and visualise scripts. This innovative tool was crafted by Charly AI Solutions, marking a significant stride in the field of automated digital content production. In a manner akin to BibleGPT, the Script-to-Image library undergoes a rigorous fine-tuning process. This involves the integration of extensive additional datasets into the DALL·E model, particularly a diverse collection of images. Such an approach enhances the model's ability to produce highly customised and contextually relevant images across a wide spectrum of user inputs, thereby broadening its application and utility in digital content generation. The Script-to-Image custom library is meant to compliment Sora once it is released, however, during the time this project is conducted it is only able to release images.

  • Animation

    • Pika is a free AI video generator. It transforms images accompanied with prompts into videos. It uses Natural Language Processing (NLP) for interpreting text prompts, alongside computer vision for image analysis, to allow an understanding a deep understanding of user inputs. Pika uses Generative Adversarial Networks (GANs) to generate new content by learning from training data. You will need to log in to use Pika, but access to most features is free.

  • Audio Narration

    • Narakeet is an online platform that used text-to-speech (TTS) technologies to transform written text into spoken voice, making it a powerful tool for creating and editing video content. The TTS engine within Narakeet converts text to audio. This technology, originally developed to aid in reading back documents on computers, has evolved to produce voices that sound natural and can accurately recognise words, phrases, and sentences. Narakeet offers flexibility in content presentation and sharing, enhancing projects with high-quality audio narration tailored with multiple voices. Most features are free to use, and it does not require any log in.

  • Music

    • SOUNDRAW is an AI music generator. Users begin by setting parameters such as mood, genre, and instruments through the "Create Music" tab, which guides the AI in generating a personalised song list. This list comprises original samples and sounds curated by our in-house team of music producers. Once a song is selected from the list, users can fine-tune it using the editor. If unsatisfied with the initial list, users have the option to regenerate it by adjusting the tags or can pay the advanced Pro Mode for further customisation. In this project, SOUNDRAW was used as an external application with Canva. It is free for use, but requires log in.

  • Video Editing & Final Touches

    • For combining the elements Canva was used. Users can access Canva for free by visiting their website and logging into their account. With Canva, you can combine various elements such as images, text, graphics, and animations to craft visually appealing and engaging multimedia content. Canva also has built in generative AI applications, including the aforementioned SOUNDRAW, that users can use to streamline the editing process.

  • Braille Conversion

    • For converting the text into braille, abcbraille was used. Braille transcription software functions by translating text characters, words, punctuation, and document formatting into equivalent braille characters. The resulting braille file can then be output to either a refreshable braille display or a braille embosser, which prints a tactile copy on paper for reading by touch. For this project, in order to be inclusive, UEB Braille Grade 1 was used as Contracted (Grade 2) braille is used by experienced braille users, making sure all braille users can understand in case this project was to be printed.

Narrating the Text

Prompt: Create a narrative script that retells the story of this "Input the digitised text"

Prompt: Re-imagine this within a scope of disabled people, and tell that story with that lens?

In a world where every person is valued not by their abilities but by their inherent worth as beings created in the image of God, there unfolds a story—a story that reimagines the birth and early life of Jesus, highlighting the significance of inclusion, empathy, and understanding, especially from the perspective of those with disabilities.

Chapter 1: The Announcement of Emmanuel

In a modest home in Nazareth, where daily life is a testament to resilience and faith, Mary and Joseph prepare for their future together. Joseph, perhaps facing his own challenges in a society where physical and mental differences are often misunderstood, is visited by an angel in a dream. This celestial messenger brings news that transcends human understanding: Mary will bear a child, not through ordinary means, but by the Holy Spirit. This child, Jesus, will be called Emmanuel, "God with us," symbolizing God's presence in a world filled with both joy and suffering, capability and limitation.

Joseph, upon waking, faces a decision. In a society where differences are often seen as burdens, accepting this child and his extraordinary origin requires a faith that sees beyond the physical, recognizing the divine purpose in every life. Moved by this vision, Joseph embraces his role, not just as a caregiver but as a father to a child who represents hope for all, including those often marginalized.

Chapter 2: A Star in the East

Meanwhile, wise men from distant lands, scholars who have faced their own societal barriers due to their unconventional beliefs and practices, observe a new star. This celestial phenomenon leads them on a journey, not just across deserts and mountains, but toward a deeper understanding of worth and dignity.

Arriving in Jerusalem, they seek the newborn king, their quest highlighting the contrast between societal expectations and God’s kingdom, where the last shall be first, and the first, last. Their journey to Bethlehem, guided by the star, becomes a metaphor for the journey of every person who has faced exclusion and longing for acceptance.

In a simple dwelling in Bethlehem, they find Jesus with Mary. Their gifts of gold, frankincense, and myrrh are symbolic, not just of kingship and divinity, but of a life that will include suffering and sacrifice—experiences familiar to those living with disabilities. Their worship is a profound recognition of Jesus' mission to embrace the overlooked and to dignify those society deems undignified.

The Flight to Egypt

As the story continues, Joseph is warned in a dream of Herod’s plans. The holy family’s flight to Egypt reflects the experiences of many who, because of their disabilities, find themselves fleeing from misunderstanding, prejudice, and violence. In Egypt, a land foreign and unfamiliar, Jesus grows up with stories of flight and refuge, instilling in him a deep empathy for the marginalized and oppressed.

This retelling of Jesus' early days through the lens of disability does not diminish the divine but highlights it. It speaks to a God who chooses the unexpected path, who values the heart over outward ability, and who is present in vulnerability and strength alike. It is a story that reminds us that in God’s kingdom, every person—regardless of physical or mental capability—is precious, valued, and called to a purpose that transcends earthly limitations.

In this reimagined narrative, the focus on disabilities illuminates the Christian belief in a God who embraces all aspects of human experience, offering hope, presence, and a promise of redemption for every person, especially those whom society might overlook or underestimate.

Reflection Point: The model's ability to adapt traditional narratives to modern themes of inclusivity, particularly from the perspective of individuals with disabilities is not too bad! In fact, this is where it can connect patterns and where humans can occasionally miss. Now in terms of reflecting on the outcome, it might be considered oversimplifying complex biblical and theological themes to fit contemporary social issues. In fact, when I told GPT-4 to reflect on this, it said it can “lead to interpretations that might feel forced or overly tailored to modern agendas, potentially alienating those who value a more traditional interpretation of biblical texts. Moreover, while the model successfully highlights societal barriers and promotes an inclusive perspective, it could enhance its approach by integrating more diverse viewpoints and deeper theological analysis to avoid the risk of projecting modern values onto historical contexts inappropriately. This would enrich the narrative with a more balanced view that respects historical authenticity while still engaging with modern concerns”. Knowing that the New Testament is perceived as alienating by a vast number of people, the model considered that the New Testament has been examined over the years through multiple lenses. It does consider the need for contextualising the facts, which is a very valid point. In terms of narrative technique, the retelling could benefit from a seamless integration of themes. At times, the emphasis on disability and societal barriers felt like a final afterthought. Balancing these elements more effectively would make the retelling robust, providing a richer understanding of the narratives that respects both their origins and their contemporary applications.

I adjusted the narrative flow and timing within the video to ensure they deeply resonate and flow smoothly AI significantly enhances the product given that it did most of what is usually human labour. But lets not get too excited and rely on generative AI! AI also brings sustainability concerns due to the energy resources it consumes, leading to a notable carbon footprint. A (not so) fun fact is that ChatGPT is a sponge! Chatgpt gulps up 500 milliliters of water every time you ask it a series of between 5 to 50 prompts or questions. Additionally, as we integrate AI into our creative processes, we must navigate copyright issues carefully, ensuring our innovations respect intellectual property laws and contribute positively to the creative community. Especially in my approach with no code and using existing models, we need to be considerate! Let us continue to push the boundaries of what we mean by creativity while also being mindful that these technologies do not exist in a vaccumm. Let us not fall into the pits of technological determinism.>

Generate the Commentary

Input

Prompt: Given this script [], and these images [], in relation to a Raised Type New Testament, generate commentary for a cultural heritage setting

[Interrputed]

Prompt: Keep it concise, to elaborate on the piece, in a place like a musuem

Prompt: Speak to museum visitors

Output

As you wander through the galleries, I invite you to pause and reflect on the powerful images before you, drawn from the Raised Type New Testament. Each scene is a tapestry of light, color, and narrative, breathing new life into timeless stories.

Picture Joseph in his humble abode, where an angel’s message heralds a future where every person is cherished. It’s a scene that speaks to the heart, asking us to consider the depth of acceptance and faith.

Now, turn your gaze to the wise men under the stars. Their journey, laden with gifts and hope, symbolizes the search for connection that transcends all barriers.

Look further to the Holy Family's flight, a poignant reminder of the resilience in the face of adversity. It’s an echo of the journeys many still undertake, seeking a place where differences are not just recognized but embraced.

Here, the Raised Type New Testament isn't just a text; it's a conversation between eras, between the seen and unseen, inviting us all to find the sacred in the spectrum of the human experience. Let these images be a reminder that everyone has a story, and every story holds a place in the halls of history and the corridors of our collective consciousness.

Discussion & Conclusion

The use of generative AI in communicating the Raised Type New Testament into accessible formats holds potential but also presents unique challenges. Effectiveness can be assessed through user engagement and feedback from many backgrounds, including museum curators, theologists, the disabled community, and content creators ensuring that these new formats truly meet their needs. While AI can facilitate the creation of accessible religious content, it also raises concerns about the accuracy and sensitivity of these translations. There is a risk of oversimplification or misinterpretation when complex theological concepts are automatically translated into different formats. Integrating technology with traditional religious practices offers opportunities to reach a broader audience and enrich their spiritual experiences, but it also necessitates ongoing dialogue between technologists, theologians, and the community to ensure that the essence of the scripture is preserved and conveyed accurately.

Reinterpreting religious texts can pose social, ethical, and theological questions. Socially, the initiative could promote greater inclusion within religious communities, offering disabled individuals more direct and meaningful engagement with these texts. As the project promised to show the object beyond religion, socially it shows how disabled people were not discussed in terms of Christianity history. Ethically, the project navigates the delicate balance of modifying sacred texts to be more inclusive while respecting their original message Theologically, this approach could prompt a re-evaluation of traditional interpretations of scriptures, especially concerning views on disability. Maintaining the integrity of the original texts while ensuring they are accessible and relevant to all, including people with disabilities, requires careful consideration of the language and methods used in such adaptations.

The Raised Type New Testament is an excellent demonstration of how religion, disability, and technology have intersected before. This project mirrors that, to intersect them once again, instead of printing it uses generative AI. This project not only have broadened accessibility of communicating the object, but also challenges traditional models of religious engagement.

Final Reflection

Reflecting on creating this project, it has opened a new way to look at biblical stories. We've reconsidered traditional narratives with a theme of disability, inspired by the context of the Raised Type New Testament. In each storyboard, I aimed to show not just scenes from the New Testament but also to bring out disability representation. This might have come across very superficial and perhaps socially accurate, but it considers the recurrent question in history—where are all the disabled people? This project wasn't just about digital arts or storytelling; it was about digging deeper into how we see and represent people in the stories we tell. By looking at these old stories through a new lens, this portfolio invites everyone to think differently about who is remembered and who is overlooked. It's a call to recognise that people of all abilities have always been part of our history and our lives; especially in social spaces like museums.

This project required much more thinking in terms of ideas rather than the implementation. In my personal judgement and my peer support groups', this project met the objectives. Credit needs to be given when its due: many thanks to my peer support group for splitting the cost together for a GPT-4 account. An extra thanks goes for your support, continous feedback, and more importantly keeping my project aligned with my chosen objects.

Wider Implications and Further Resources

Copyright

  • Copyright in generative AI is controversial topic where ownership of the output generated by machine learning models is contingent on factors such as the input data, human creative input, autonomy of the model, contractual agreements, and the application of fair use principles. Determining copyright ownership becomes intricate when considering the influence of training data, the extent of human involvement in the generation process, and the evolving legal interpretations surrounding AI-generated content. In this case of this project, I used Dall-e, owned by OpenAI that are not transparent of their training data. There is a pressing need for robust legal and ethical frameworks to clarify ownership, attribution, licensing, and fair use practices, ensuring that the rights of creators and users are appropriately balanced in the digital age. Here's an interesting opinion piece to read about OpenAI's lack of transperancy.

    • Enviornmental Impact

  • What happens behind the scenes with generative AI is frequently overlooked; generative AI has considerable effects on the environment. This highlights the importance of refining prompts to achieve the desired results without excessive generation. This constraint influenced the extent of my experimentation with various prompts and my efforts to replicate results. For future reference, it might be better to conduct further readings on each model and the art of prompt crafting. This challenge extends beyond GANs, as each programming language carries its environmental footprint related to processing. Therefore, before fully transitioning to AI applications with art, it is crucial to enhance our comprehension of how to interact with these technologies efficiently.
    • Read more on estimating the environmental impact of Generative-AI services using an LCA-based methodology

    Other potential areas with AI & Religion

  • The potential of generative AI is highlighted in its ability to handle vast datasets and complex categorisation tasks, which are critical in fields like religion where data are extensive and multifaceted. For instance, generative AI can assist in the classification of religious texts, predicting trends in religious behavior, and even in generating models that simulate religious phenomena. This capability extends beyond mere computational tasks to involve deeper theoretical implications, such as the re-examination of religious categories and the introduction of novel methodologies in religious studies. Thus, generative AI not only offers a new toolset for scholars but also prompts a reconsideration of the methodologies and theoretical frameworks in religious studies. You can find more on these two interesting papers The AI Creation Meme: A Case Study of the New Visibility of Religion in Artificial Intelligence Discourse and AI in Religion, AI for Religion, AI and Religion: Towards a theory of religious studies and artificial intelligence
